{"questionId":"27997","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Adesh is designing a glass. The glass has an inner surface and an outer surface. Part of&nbsp;the cross section of his design is shown in the following graph, where the shaded region&nbsp;represents the glass. The two surfaces meet at the top of the glass. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> unit represents <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/c74d0ba01c82ca4cb7c783ed4d3187e1539a0f91.png\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">The inner surface is modelled by&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>p</mi></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\"><br>The outer surface is modelled by&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mfenced open=\"{\" close=\"\"><mtable columnspacing=\"1.4ex\" columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mtext>for</mtext><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo></mtd><mtd><mtext>for</mtext><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>p</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>